York's attorney general lays out
details of his new
investigation,

00:19.586 --> 00:22.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and an Exxon vice
president responds.

00:22.489 --> 00:27.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Also ahead this
Tuesday: in the footsteps of our
ancestors. Journalist Paul

00:27.694 --> 00:32.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Salopek walks around the world
to uncover humans' prehistoric
journey.

00:32.566 --> 00:36.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK, Fellow, National
Geographic: The walk has opened
up the vista to me in

00:36.570 --> 00:40.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both space and time, where I can
see the connections between all
of these stories and I see how

00:40.574 --> 00:43.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
history informs everything
that's happening today.

00:43.777 --> 00:49.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And "Breaking
Bad" actor Bryan Cranston talks
about playing a blacklisted

00:49.182 --> 00:53.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
screenwriter at the height of
the Red Scare in the 1950s.

00:53.453 --> 00:58.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRYAN CRANSTON, Actor: A lot of
people will look back and say
that he's a hero. There

00:58.225 --> 01:02.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are other people who will say,
he was no hero, he's a dirty red
commie or whatever. And I

01:02.696 --> 01:06.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suppose the point of the movie
is that all opinions are
welcome.

01:06.566 --> 01:13.440 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

01:13.440 --> 01:17.577 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
