Moscow Olympics in 1980, but
said later that nothing was
gained

06:31.591 --> 06:35.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from it. Helmut Schmidt
was 96 years old.

06:35.528 --> 06:41.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And legendary New
Orleans musician Allen Toussaint
died in Spain today after

06:41.434 --> 06:46.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a heart attack. He was a pianist
and performer who wrote and
produced a long line of hits

06:46.806 --> 06:51.945 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
for himself and others,
including "Working in a Coal
Mine" and "Lady Marmalade."

06:51.945 --> 06:57.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here he is recording "Who's
Gonna Help Brother Get Further?"
for a 2006 album with Elvis

06:57.817 --> 07:04.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Costello, as seen in
a BBC documentary.

07:04.157 --> 07:10.363 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(MUSIC)

07:10.363 --> 07:32.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Toussaint joined
the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
in 1998 and was awarded

07:32.452 --> 07:38.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the National Humanities Medal in
2013. At his death, he was 77
years old.

07:38.358 --> 07:43.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Still to come on the
"NewsHour": accused of a
cover-up, Exxon's own research

07:43.530 --> 07:48.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on climate change; the largest
strike yet for a $15 minimum
wage; the man who's walking

07:48.902 --> 07:55.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
across the world, and much more.

07:55.075 --> 08:08.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: First, a new tack
in the battle over climate
change: going after energy
companies

08:08.488 --> 08:12.158 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for alleged financial fraud.

08:12.158 --> 08:17.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New York State Attorney General
Eric Schneiderman recently
subpoenaed oil giant ExxonMobil,

08:17.931 --> 08:24.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
apparently seeking documents
that might show the company had
downplayed the risks to profits

08:24.070 --> 08:30.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and therefore to investors of
stronger regulations on burning
fossil fuels. Exxon's history
has

08:30.110 --> 08:36.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been the subject of recent
reporting by Inside Climate
News, The Los Angeles Times and
others.

08:36.616 --> 08:41.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The reporting has alleged the
company misled the public about
what its own scientists found

08:41.388 --> 08:45.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about the risks of climate
change and greenhouse gases.

08:45.325 --> 08:51.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here is a clip of a video
produced by PBS' "Frontline" in
collaboration with Inside
Climate

08:51.998 --> 08:57.137 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
News, a not-for-profit
journalism organization that
covers energy and the
environment.

08:57.137 --> 09:04.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: Proponents of the global
warming theory say that higher
levels of greenhouse gases

09:04.010 --> 09:10.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are causing world temperatures
to rise and that burning fossil
fuels is the reason.

09:10.183 --> 09:14.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The scientific evidence remains
inconclusive as to whether human
activities affect the

09:14.320 --> 09:19.626 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
global climate.

09:19.626 --> 09:29.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: We found a trail of
comes that go back to 1977.

09:29.869 --> 09:36.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Exxon knew carbon dioxide was
increasing in the atmosphere,
that combustion of fossil

09:36.576 --> 09:46.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fuels was driving it, and that
this posed a threat to Exxon. At
that time, Exxon understood

09:46.853 --> 09:53.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very quickly that governments
would probably take action to
reduce fossil fuel consumption.

09:53.460 --> 09:57.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're smart people, great
scientists, and they saw the
writing on the wall.

09:57.197 --> 10:00.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That's a
"Frontline" excerpt.

10:00.266 --> 10:04.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I spoke earlier this evening
with New York State Attorney
General Eric Schneiderman.

10:04.537 --> 10:08.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Welcome, Attorney General
Eric Schneiderman.

10:08.808 --> 10:14.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let me just begin by asking in
-- what is it that ExxonMobil
has done, in your view,

10:14.581 --> 10:17.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that caused you to launch
this investigation?

10:17.150 --> 10:19.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC SCHNEIDERMAN, New York
Attorney General: We have been
looking at the energy sector

10:19.719 --> 10:26.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
generally for a number of years,
and have -- had several
investigations that relate

10:26.793 --> 10:31.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the phenomenon of global
warming, climate change, and the
human contribution to it.

10:31.965 --> 10:38.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we have subpoenaed, issued a
broad subpoena to Exxon because
of public statements they

10:38.271 --> 10:44.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have made and how they have
really shifted their point of
view on this in terms of their

10:44.010 --> 10:49.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public presentation and public
reporting over the last few
decades.

10:49.716 --> 10:55.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the 1980s, they were putting
out some very good studies about
climate change. They were

10:55.021 --> 11:00.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
compared to Bell Labs as being
at the leadership of doing good
scientific work. And then they

11:00.660 --> 11:05.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
changed tactics for some reason,
and their numerous statements
over the last 20 years

11:05.899 --> 11:11.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or so that question climate
change, whether it's happening,
that claim that there is no

11:11.404 --> 11:14.307 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
competent model for
climate change.

11:14.307 --> 11:20.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we're very interested in
seeing what science Exxon has
been using for its own purposes,

11:20.513 --> 11:26.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because they're tremendously
active in offshore oil drilling
in the Arctic, for example,
where

11:26.319 --> 11:30.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
global warming is happening at a
much more rapid rate than in
more temperate zones. Were

11:30.557 --> 11:34.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they using the best science and
the most competent models for
their own purposes, but then
telling

11:34.994 --> 11:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the public, the regulators and
shareholders, that no competent
models existed?

11:40.500 --> 11:42.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Things like that. We're
interested in what they were
using internally and what they
were

11:42.368 --> 11:43.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
telling the world.

11:43.770 --> 11:48.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what law
would be violated by doing this?

11:48.408 --> 11:53.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC SCHNEIDERMAN: Well, in New
York, we have laws against
defrauding the public,
defrauding

11:53.012 --> 11:55.915 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
consumers, defrauding
shareholders.

11:55.915 --> 12:00.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're at the beginning of the
investigation. We have to see
what documents are in there,

12:00.453 --> 12:05.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but certainly all of the claims
would lie in some form of fraud.

12:05.658 --> 12:10.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I'm sure
you're not surprised to know
Exxon is categorically denying
this.

12:10.129 --> 12:15.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The CEO, Rex Tillerson, said
this week nothing could be
further from the truth.

12:15.535 --> 12:20.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In the company's written
statement, they start out by
saying for many years, they have
included

12:20.373 --> 12:25.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the information they have
about the risks of climate
change in their public filings,

12:25.311 --> 12:28.047 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
in their reports
to shareholders.

12:28.047 --> 12:30.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC SCHNEIDERMAN: We know that
they have been issuing public
statements that are at

12:30.516 --> 12:34.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
odds with that, and that they
have been funding organizations
that are even more aggressive

12:34.854 --> 12:38.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
climate change deniers.

12:38.024 --> 12:42.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they have made numerous
statement, both Exxon officials
and in Exxon reports, but

12:42.495 --> 12:47.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also through these organizations
