better for their own bottom
line?

14:48.855 --> 14:54.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC SCHNEIDERMAN: Well, there's
nothing wrong with advocating
for your own company.

14:54.327 --> 15:00.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What you're not allowed to do is
commit fraud. You're not allowed
to have the best climate

15:00.166 --> 15:06.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
change science that you're using
to build -- in your planning of
offshore oil towers

15:06.005 --> 15:10.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the Arctic, where you have to
take into account rising sea
levels and the melting

15:10.309 --> 15:14.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the permafrost and things
like that. If you're using that
internally, but what you're

15:14.413 --> 15:18.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
putting out to the world,
directly and through these
climate denial organizations, is
completely

15:18.417 --> 15:21.220 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
in conflict with
that, that's not OK.

15:21.220 --> 15:23.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: New York State
Attorney General Eric Schmitt,
we thank you.

15:23.923 --> 15:26.325 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ERIC SCHNEIDERMAN: Thank you.

15:26.325 --> 15:30.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And joining me
now is Kenneth Cohen. He is vice
president for public and

15:30.797 --> 15:34.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
government affairs with
ExxonMobil Corporation.

15:34.100 --> 15:36.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Kenneth Cohen, welcome.

15:36.269 --> 15:42.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let me just begin by asking flat
out, has Exxon in any way misled
or been dishonest

15:42.508 --> 15:46.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with the public about what it
knows about climate change?

15:46.245 --> 15:47.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KENNETH COHEN, Vice President
for Public and Government
Affairs, ExxonMobil: Well, Judy,

15:47.647 --> 15:52.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
first, thank you for the
invitation to come on tonight's
program.

15:52.585 --> 16:00.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I also appreciate opening
with that question, because the
answer is a simple no. And what

16:00.626 --> 16:06.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the facts will show is that the
company has been engaged for
many decades in a two-pronged

16:06.732 --> 16:09.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
activity here.

16:09.268 --> 16:15.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First, we take the risks of
climate change seriously. And we
also have been working to

16:15.641 --> 16:20.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understand the science of
climate change. And that
activity started in the late
'70s

16:20.680 --> 16:25.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and has continued up to the
present time. Our scientists
have produced over 150 papers,

16:25.985 --> 16:30.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
50 of which have been part of
peer-reviewed publications.

16:30.723 --> 16:37.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our scientists participate in
the U.N.'s climate body. We have
been participating in the U.N.

16:37.163 --> 16:43.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
activities beginning in 1988,
running through the present
time. At the same time, we have

16:43.269 --> 16:48.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
also been engaged in
discussions on policy.

16:48.274 --> 16:55.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in the discussions on
policy, for example, in the late
'90s, we were part of a large

16:55.715 --> 17:01.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
business coalition that opposed
adoption in the U.S. of the
Kyoto protocol. Now, why did

17:01.420 --> 17:07.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we do that? We opposed the Kyoto
protocol because it would have
exempted from its application

17:07.493 --> 17:13.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over two-thirds of the world's
emitters. Think about that. And
that was in 1997.

17:13.099 --> 17:18.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Going forward, if that policy
were in effect today, it would
have excluded almost 80 percent

17:18.237 --> 17:23.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the world's emissions. So
that wasn't a good policy
approach.

17:23.476 --> 17:27.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me ask
you about one of the points that
the attorney general

17:27.013 --> 17:32.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made. He said Exxon over the
last few decades, in his words,
has shifted tactics, from taking

17:32.685 --> 17:36.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
climate change seriously,
engaging in serious research,
to, he said, much more recently

17:36.656 --> 17:40.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
questioning whether
it's happening at all.

17:40.426 --> 17:44.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is that an accurate, a fair
description of the shift that's
taken place?

17:44.530 --> 17:49.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KENNETH COHEN: No, it's not.
And the facts are as follows.

17:49.235 --> 17:55.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have endeavored with -- to
understand the science of this
very complex subject, as I

17:55.574 --> 18:00.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mentioned, beginning in the '70s
and running to the present time.
This is a very complex

18:00.680 --> 18:05.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
area. This is a very
complex system, climate.

18:05.785 --> 18:10.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we discovered, what our
scientists discovered, working
in conjunction with the U.S.
government,

18:10.656 --> 18:15.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the Department of Energy,
working in conjunction with some
of the leading research

18:15.127 --> 18:20.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
institutions around the world in
the '70s and the '80s, was that
the tools available

18:20.399 --> 18:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the science to get a handle on
the risk, these tools needed to
develop, and we, for example,

18:28.240 --> 18:34.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were part of developing, working
with others, some of the complex
modeling that is used

18:34.580 --> 18:36.782 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today.

18:36.782 --> 18:45.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, today, that work continues.
Now, on the policy side, we have
to remember that ExxonMobil

18:45.658 --> 18:50.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a large energy provider, one
of the world's largest energy
companies. We have a two-pronged

18:50.930 --> 18:56.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
challenge in front of us. We
produce energy that the modern
world runs on.

18:56.669 --> 19:02.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we strive to do is
produce that energy while at the
same time reducing the
environmental

19:02.475 --> 19:06.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
footprint associated with our
operations and, most
importantly, with consumers' use
of the

19:06.012 --> 19:07.747 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
energy.

19:07.747 --> 19:11.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I think
people understand that, but I
think what is striking was his

19:11.884 --> 19:15.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- was the attorney general's
comment that Exxon -- what he's
concerned about and wants

19:15.888 --> 19:22.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to know is whether Exxon was
using one set of scientific
models to do its work in the

19:22.228 --> 19:27.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Arctic, for example, where Exxon
has been engaged in drilling,
and on the other hand

19:27.333 --> 19:31.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
telling the public, telling its
shareholders a very different
set of facts about the state

19:31.804 --> 19:33.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of climate change.

19:33.873 --> 19:40.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KENNETH COHEN: Well, the facts
will show that the company has
been engaged with, not only

19:40.379 --> 19:44.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on our own, but with -- in
conjunction with some of the
leading researchers.

19:44.683 --> 19:51.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our view of this very complex
subject over the years, over the
decades has mirrored that

19:51.824 --> 19:56.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the broader scientific
community. That is to say, the
discussions that have taken

19:56.829 --> 20:02.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
place inside our company, among
our scientists mirror the
discussions that have been
taking

20:02.168 --> 20:05.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
place and the work that's been
taking place by the broader
scientific community.

20:05.471 --> 20:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's what the facts will show.

20:07.606 --> 20:13.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just final
question. He made a point of
saying that Exxon has funded a

20:13.145 --> 20:18.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
number of organizations that he
said that have been openly
climate change deniers. He

20:18.617 --> 20:22.354 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
mentioned the American
Enterprise Institute. He
mentioned the American Petroleum
Institute

20:22.354 --> 20:24.490 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
and the American
Legislative Exchange.

20:24.490 --> 20:26.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Has Exxon been funding
these organizations?

20:26.725 --> 20:31.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KENNETH COHEN: Well, the answer
is yes. And I will let those
organizations respond for

20:31.163 --> 20:33.132 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
themselves.

20:33.132 --> 20:40.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I will tell you that what we
have been engaged in, both -- we
have been focused on

20:40.072 --> 20:44.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understanding the science,
participating with the broader
scientific community in
developing

20:44.076 --> 20:49.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the science, while at the same
time participating in
understanding what would be and
working

20:49.782 --> 20:54.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with policy-makers on what would
be appropriate policy responses
to this evolving body of

20:54.820 --> 20:56.755 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
science.

20:56.755 --> 21:03.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's why we were involved with
large business coalitions
challenging the adoption of the

21:03.796 --> 21:10.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kyoto protocol in the United
States. And we then moved to
oppose, for example, early
adoption

21:10.803 --> 21:15.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of cap-and-trade approaches in
the U.S. One of the earlier
approaches in the last decade

21:15.808 --> 21:19.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
would have exempted, for
example, coal from its
operations.

21:19.745 --> 21:25.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we favor the adoption --
policy-makers should consider
policy and should adopt policy.

21:25.951 --> 21:32.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have disclosed the risks of
climate change to our investors
beginning in the middle part

21:32.324 --> 21:35.794 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of the last decade and
extending to the present time.

21:35.794 --> 21:39.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Kenneth Cohen,
vice president for ExxonMobil,
we appreciate having your

21:39.365 --> 21:42.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
point of view, as we do the
New York attorney general.

21:42.935 --> 21:45.604 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

21:45.604 --> 21:51.677 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KENNETH COHEN: Thank you.

21:51.677 --> 21:58.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As New York Governor
Andrew Cuomo moved to raise that
state's minimum wage to

21:58.784 --> 22:04.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
$15 an hour today, a national
battle over pay played out from
coast to coast, as fast

22:04.890 --> 22:10.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
food and other low-wage workers
took their protests to the
streets.

22:10.596 --> 22:15.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Thousands of workers pushing for
an increase in the minimum wage
were expected to walk

22:15.601 --> 22:22.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
off the job in as many as 270
cities today, with protests in
more than 200 others.

22:22.441 --> 22:26.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Maybe I wouldn't have to
work two jobs, and maybe I
wouldn't have to work seven days

22:26.946 --> 22:31.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
