just to make a little holiday

22:31.417 --> 22:33.619 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pay extra.

22:33.619 --> 22:39.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Organizers who favor
raising the federal wage to $15
an hour planned for today's

22:39.558 --> 22:45.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actions to be the largest strike
ever by employees of the fast
food industry.

22:45.064 --> 22:51.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The federal minimum wage has
been set at $7.25 an hour since
2009. Democratic presidential

22:51.303 --> 22:55.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
candidates Martin O'Malley and
Bernie Sanders back the $15
push.

22:55.741 --> 23:00.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (VT-I),
Presidential Candidate: They
have had the impact of moving
Los Angeles

23:00.279 --> 23:03.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and San Francisco and other
cities to raise the minimum
wage. They are doing it.

23:03.916 --> 23:08.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But some Democrats
say the hike should be lower,
$12 an hour, in part because

23:08.921 --> 23:13.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some cities and states have
raised minimums on their own.
Hillary Clinton and Labor
Secretary

23:13.859 --> 23:19.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tom Perez have said they support
a $12 measure now in Congress.
But many businesses and most

23:19.298 --> 23:24.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Republicans say raising the
wage that high would cost jobs.

23:24.970 --> 23:28.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly all of the Republican
candidates who will debate in
Milwaukee tonight support
keeping

23:28.073 --> 23:33.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the minimum wage well
below $15 an hour.

23:33.712 --> 23:37.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Continuing our coverage of this
ongoing debate, we turn tonight
to a prominent labor economist

23:37.983 --> 23:43.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who believes wages should be
raised, but not so fast and not
so high.

23:43.222 --> 23:46.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Alan Krueger is the former
chairman of President Obama's
Council of Economic Advisers,
and

23:46.692 --> 23:49.862 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
he's now a professor of
economics and public affairs at
Princeton University.

23:49.862 --> 23:52.765 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome, Professor Krueger.

23:52.765 --> 23:59.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have written that the $15
raise -- you have written that
raising the minimum wage

23:59.338 --> 24:03.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to $15 an hour is a risk not
worth taking. Why is it not?

24:03.876 --> 24:05.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER, Former Chairman,
White House Council of Economic
Advisers: Well, first

24:05.878 --> 24:10.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of all, Gwen, I would draw a
distinction between the worker
activism that you highlighted at

24:10.716 --> 24:14.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the beginning and the
federal minimum wage.

24:14.820 --> 24:20.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's wonderful to see
workers get more engaged. We
have a long tradition in

24:20.159 --> 24:26.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this country of promoting worker
voice, worker activism to
support their own pay. And I
think

24:26.498 --> 24:31.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there are certainly some sectors
that can handle a $15-an-hour
minimum, but at a national

24:31.303 --> 24:34.740 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
level, I think that's
a different story.

24:34.740 --> 24:40.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And just to give you an example,
the research I did two decades
ago with David Card of Berkeley,

24:40.813 --> 24:46.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we looked at what happened when
the minimum wage in New Jersey
went from $4.25 an hour

24:46.452 --> 24:51.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to $5.15 an hour, which is the
equivalent today of going from
$7.25 to $8.60 an hour,

24:51.323 --> 24:54.793 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
very far from $15.

24:54.793 --> 24:59.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what we found was that an
increase at this more moderate
level, well above where

24:59.732 --> 25:03.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it is today, didn't have an
adverse effect on employment.
Other studies have reached

25:03.202 --> 25:03.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a similar conclusion.

25:03.402 --> 25:03.669 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

25:03.669 --> 25:04.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Pardon me.

25:04.269 --> 25:06.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALAN KRUEGER: Yes.

25:06.004 --> 25:08.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So you're suggesting
-- just moving it to today for a
moment -- that the difference

25:08.240 --> 25:12.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
between $12 and $15
an hour is what?

25:12.444 --> 25:18.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: No, the point I'm
making is an increase to $12 at
a national level is

25:18.784 --> 25:21.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a considerable increase. It
would put the minimum wage above
where it's been in the

25:21.987 --> 25:25.891 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
history of the United States.

25:25.891 --> 25:32.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if you move it up to $15 an
hour nationwide, I'm concerned
that that is well beyond what

25:32.831 --> 25:35.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we have seen in past research.
And if I were advising the
president today, I would say

25:35.701 --> 25:38.470 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think that's a risky level.

25:38.470 --> 25:43.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Why is it even
necessary for there to be a
federal floor, when so many
states

25:43.542 --> 25:47.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and cities are stepping in?
That's what a lot of Republicans
are saying.

25:47.413 --> 25:52.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: Well, most of the
Republican candidates favor
keeping the minimum wage

25:52.651 --> 25:55.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where it is or getting rid of
it, from what I have heard in
the earlier debates. And I

25:55.020 --> 25:59.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
hope they get asked
about that tonight.

25:59.224 --> 26:05.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have in some sense a
nationwide labor market. The
minimum wage is a standard of
fairness.

26:05.631 --> 26:11.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also use the minimum wage to
help redress the imbalance in
bargaining power between

26:11.703 --> 26:16.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
employers and firms. And I think
if we abolish the federal
minimum wage, which is what you

26:16.775 --> 26:20.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
asked about, you would have some
states that didn't have a
minimum wage at all or a very

26:20.846 --> 26:25.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
low one, and that would be
unfair to other states that have
a higher minimum wage.

26:25.017 --> 26:31.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we have a long history in the
U.S. of having a federal floor,
and raising it from time

26:31.390 --> 26:38.063 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to time. It's stalled
considerably after adjusting for
inflation in the 1980s. And I
think it's

26:38.063 --> 26:44.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
only fair to put it back in real
terms where it was previously or
a bit above it.

26:44.470 --> 26:47.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, risk is
obviously in the eye of the
beholder. And you say your
research

26:47.239 --> 26:50.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has shown that there will not be
jobs lost as a result of raising
the minimum wage even

26:50.709 --> 26:53.912 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to $12.

26:53.912 --> 26:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, how do you support that
argument? Because it seems to
make sense that if you have to

26:57.316 --> 27:00.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pay more, that you're going to
have to employ fewer people.

27:00.185 --> 27:03.722 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ALAN KRUEGER: Well,
a couple of things.

27:03.722 --> 27:08.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One, you look around the world,
and countries that have raised
their minimum wage to around

27:08.460 --> 27:13.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that level have not seen job
losses. The best work most
recently has been done looking
at

27:13.232 --> 27:19.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the U.K., which has a low pay
commission, bipartisan
commission, employers, labor
groups,

27:19.104 --> 27:21.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
academics, which repeatedly
finds no adverse effects from
raising the minimum wage, but

27:21.707 --> 27:24.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a big help for low-wage workers.

27:24.710 --> 27:30.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at a theoretical level, the
labor market is not as
competitive as we often teach in

27:30.115 --> 27:35.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our first introductory lectures.
There are a lot of frictions in
the job market, and

27:35.087 --> 27:40.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what many employers find is that
with a higher minimum wage, they
have lower turnover. They

27:40.893 --> 27:45.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get more job applicants. They
can fill vacancies that they
have. Morale is higher.
Productivity

27:45.797 --> 27:49.968 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is higher, and that enables them
to afford the higher minimum
wage.

27:49.968 --> 27:54.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that's the case up
to a certain level. And if the
minimum wage exceeds a certain

27:54.339 --> 27:57.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
level, then I think you start
to find undesirable effects.

27:57.743 --> 28:01.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: All right, Alan
Krueger, thank you very much.

28:01.880 --> 28:11.089 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALAN KRUEGER: My pleasure.

28:11.089 --> 28:17.896 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

28:17.896 --> 28:23.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
ban on soccer headers, amid
fears of concussions; and actor

28:23.702 --> 28:29.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bryan Cranston on his new film
about Hollywood and communism.

28:29.041 --> 28:35.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, journalist Paul
Salopek spent his career
covering the news overseas and

28:35.213 --> 28:39.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
jetting around the globe, until
he realized that walking around
the world might just give

28:39.384 --> 28:42.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
him the deeper insights
he was searching for.

28:42.454 --> 28:46.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Hari Sreenivasan met up
with Salopek for a stroll.

28:46.058 --> 28:50.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK, Fellow, National
Geographic: There is something
not in your brain, but

28:50.362 --> 28:54.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
almost in your backbone, about
the rhythm of walking, this A/B,
A/B. It's the pace of

28:54.600 --> 28:57.069 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a heartbeat.

28:57.069 --> 29:03.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On a high
country cool morning, Paul
Salopek is out for a walk. But
his walk

29:03.442 --> 29:10.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is unlike any you or I might
take. On this morning, he is
nearing mile 4,000 of a trek

29:10.816 --> 29:17.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that began in January 2013 in
Ethiopia's Great Rift Valley,
the wellspring of ancient
humankind.

29:17.022 --> 29:21.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: This whole project
is about two things. It's about
the past and the future.

29:21.727 --> 29:26.098 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And the past element is
following our first ancestors
who spread out of Africa during

29:26.098 --> 29:31.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Stone Age, so, following the
footsteps of some very old and
intrepid pioneers.

29:31.870 --> 29:36.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He calls this
project the Out of Eden Walk,
and he will end it some

29:36.942 --> 29:44.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time in six or seven years at
the very southern tip of South
America, after logging 21,000

29:44.916 --> 29:51.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
miles. That's about 30 million
footsteps, for those of you
counting yours every day.

29:51.156 --> 29:55.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The two-time Pulitzer
Prize-winning foreign
correspondent was used to
dropping into war

29:55.160 --> 30:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
zones and driving his way out as
fast as possible. But so far on
this trip, he's walked through

30:01.533 --> 30:08.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some of the conflict zones of
the Middle East, now on an
assignment that is his lifetime.

30:08.473 --> 30:11.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With support from the National
Geographic Society, the Nieman
and Knight Foundations

30:11.943 --> 30:15.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and others, he has walked
across deserts and mountains.

30:15.313 --> 30:17.983 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, why do this?

30:17.983 --> 30:25.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: There has got to
be a space to slow down, analyze
and absorb more meaningful

30:25.490 --> 30:29.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
information. I don't think we
need more information. I think
we need more meaning.

30:29.394 --> 30:35.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What kind of
context are you able to get when
you are walking vs. when

30:35.067 --> 30:38.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we get there in cars
and planes and trains?

30:38.370 --> 30:43.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Walking has shown
me that the boundaries between
stories are permeable,

30:43.275 --> 30:48.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in that one story bleeds into
another, because human life
bleeds into each other. And so

30:48.547 --> 30:51.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
walking between stories shows me
connections that didn't -- I
didn't used to see when I

30:51.717 --> 30:53.618 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would parachute in.

30:53.618 --> 30:56.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And what are
we saying? What is humanity
telling you?

30:56.254 --> 31:00.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: The same stories
over and over again. It's the
same classic stories of
complaint,

31:00.592 --> 31:08.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of joy, of aspiration, of hope,
of hopes dashed. And I never get
tired of them.

31:08.300 --> 31:11.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We caught up
with him in Southern Georgia's
Caucasus Mountains, near

31:11.970 --> 31:17.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Armenia, where the walk was
stopped late last fall at this
destroyed Soviet-era building.

31:17.542 --> 31:22.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Last November, we
had just crossed the Turkish
border, and it was very bad
weather.

31:22.214 --> 31:27.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was snowing, it was sleeting,
very cold both during the day
and at night. We came

31:27.586 --> 31:32.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down, and with frozen feet had
to break through a frozen river,
plunging in up to our thighs.

31:32.457 --> 31:35.694 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
And we were very
afraid of hypothermia.

31:35.694 --> 31:39.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Salopek and
three walking partners found
this "Spotlight". One man set

31:39.698 --> 31:43.902 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his gloves alight to start
a fire and stay warm.

31:43.902 --> 31:48.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: On a November
night a year ago, this was
heaven. This was better than a
five-star

31:48.340 --> 31:50.475 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
hotel.

31:50.475 --> 31:55.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Then he waited
here in Tbilisi, the capital of
Georgia, for a lot longer than

31:55.414 --> 31:59.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he planned. He was stuck in what
he calls a
geopolitically-induced storm,
waiting for

31:59.651 --> 32:03.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
visas that would determine
the rest of his route.

32:03.221 --> 32:06.591 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A hundred thousand years ago,
the problems were different
here, in this land littered

32:06.591 --> 32:10.095 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with volcanic boulders
from ancient eruptions.

32:10.095 --> 32:15.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SALOPEK: When our
ancestors, the first people who
walked out of Africa, passed
through

32:15.000 --> 32:21.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this region, their big obstacles
were glaciers and big animals
that would eat them or droughts

32:21.406 --> 32:28.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or famines. Today, mine is these
ethnic fault lines and these
imaginary walls, these imaginary

32:28.113 --> 32:33.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
glaciers called borders. And
they have knocked me sideways,
way off my intended track.

32:33.718 --> 32:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Months of
back-and-forth talks with
regional governments made it
clear

32:37.455 --> 32:43.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that his original plan to walk
across Iran and points east
wouldn't work.

32:43.195 --> 32:46.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Finally, he set a route from
Georgia that will pass through
Azerbaijan, on to Kazakstan

32:46.731 --> 32:48.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and beyond.

32:48.567 --> 32:53.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: This doesn't look
like much, but this ruin on the
high plateau of Southern

32:53.505 --> 32:59.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Georgia is the beginning of
phase two of the Out of Eden
Walk. So, this is the gateway

32:59.277 --> 33:01.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the Orient for me. From here,
I'm leaving the Caucasus, going
on the old silk roads

33:01.780 --> 33:04.282 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to China.

33:04.282 --> 33:09.688 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So at
mid-morning on October 20,
Salopek set out, with the world
revealed

33:09.688 --> 33:14.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
before him one step after the
other, on this day up to a
mountain pass at more than 9,000

33:14.659 --> 33:16.995 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
feet.

33:16.995 --> 33:21.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Down the other side, Salopek and
his walking partner spent the
night in the small village

33:21.666 --> 33:27.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Mamishlari, a village of
ethnic Azeris from Azerbaijan.
They were taken in by the

33:27.939 --> 33:33.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nasibov family; 72-year-old
Ziaudoin and his 70-year-old
wife, Azmat (ph), married as
teenagers.

33:33.545 --> 33:38.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is a tough farm life, on the
edge, really, of civilization.

33:38.283 --> 33:42.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: We came around the
corner of this mountain river
and here was this village

33:42.020 --> 33:44.689 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
that we didn't
even know existed.

33:44.689 --> 33:48.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The first reaction was
curiosity. When I finally told
him, well, actually, I have
hiked all

33:48.426 --> 33:52.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the way from Africa, that was
the surprise moment, and there
was laughter around that

33:52.063 --> 33:58.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
table. And there was a lively
exchange about, oh, you have got
to be crazy.

33:58.336 --> 34:02.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ZIAUDOIN NASIBOV, Farmer
(through translator): I don't
think he is crazy. I actually
thought

34:02.540 --> 34:05.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he was quite enlightened,
because they actually want to
walk across the world and see
what's

34:05.911 --> 34:09.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out there. You might not notice
a place, but when you walk by on
foot, you see it, and

34:09.681 --> 34:13.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
appreciate it for
what it actually is.

34:13.184 --> 34:19.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Ziaud also has
basically joined the walk
because he showed us the way.

34:19.624 --> 34:24.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All along his
route, Salopek has been joined
by walking partners, who
function

34:24.696 --> 34:31.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as guides, translators and
companions. In Georgia, that
partner was Dima Bit-Suleiman.

34:31.336 --> 34:33.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is the reaction of most of
the people you bump into when
you tell them what he's

34:33.638 --> 34:35.373 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing?

34:35.373 --> 34:38.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIMA BIT-SULEIMAN, Guide: They
go like, yes, yes, yes, coming
from Africa. On walk? What

34:38.310 --> 34:39.577 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
do you mean?

34:39.577 --> 34:41.379 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

34:41.379 --> 34:44.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIMA BIT-SULEIMAN: That's like,
usually, they kind of don't
believe and they say, why is

34:44.950 --> 34:48.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
he doing it? What is
he trying to find out?

34:48.286 --> 34:50.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about
when they figure out that he is
trying to go to the end of

34:50.889 --> 34:52.424 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the world?

34:52.424 --> 34:54.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIMA BIT-SULEIMAN: And then it's
even worse. And then they really
ask, like, what is he

34:54.893 --> 34:55.627 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
searching for?

34:55.627 --> 34:56.027 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

34:56.027 --> 34:57.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

34:57.963 --> 35:03.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIMA BIT-SULEIMAN: Like, why is
he doing that? I don't think
there is an easy answer.

35:03.134 --> 35:06.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: After passing
through boggy lowlands, where
horsemen emerged from fairy

35:06.838 --> 35:12.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tale fogs, Salopek arrived
at a village, Ipnari.

35:12.410 --> 35:20.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Largely abandoned, it revealed a
much deeper history, nearby, a
Bronze Age wine store,

35:20.652 --> 35:23.822 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
5,000-year-old fermentation
vats sunken in the ground.

35:23.822 --> 35:26.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: You're talking
about the beginning of
civilization. Georgians were
already drinking.

35:26.257 --> 35:28.259 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:28.259 --> 35:34.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: The walk has
opened up the vista to me in
both space and time, where I can

35:34.966 --> 35:37.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see the connections between all
of these stories and I see how
history informs everything
that's

35:37.635 --> 35:42.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happening today.

35:42.640 --> 35:48.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Time pools in certain valleys,
and it runs like a river through
certain canyon systems,

35:48.179 --> 35:53.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
certain plains. And every step
you take could be in a different
era. And so here we are

35:53.551 --> 35:59.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
coming up to another one, and I
think that the task now is to
kind of go slowly.

35:59.457 --> 36:04.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But, for now,
his steps were taking him toward
the village of Boslebi,

36:04.429 --> 36:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Georgia. And as the evening
gathered, Salopek explained one
mind-boggling facet of this

36:08.366 --> 36:11.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
grand experiment.

36:11.903 --> 36:15.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
More often than not, when he
sets out each morning, he has
little idea where he will

36:15.540 --> 36:17.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sleep that night.

36:17.909 --> 36:21.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: We're going to
draw attention, obviously, and
just start greeting people

36:21.212 --> 36:23.782 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and start striking
up conversations.

36:23.782 --> 36:29.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And it is this
exact moment, first contact in a
village, that Salopek was

36:29.788 --> 36:33.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hesitant to have us film up
close. It's hard making a first
impression with a camera crew

36:33.625 --> 36:36.828 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in tow.

36:36.828 --> 36:41.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This day, five minutes after
this scene and after meeting two
other people in town, they

36:41.366 --> 36:43.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
both had a place to
stay for the night.

36:43.802 --> 36:48.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You don't plan out every step
of the way, so to speak.

36:48.173 --> 36:51.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Yes, it's hard to
explain to readers who think
that I have got a team back

36:51.242 --> 36:57.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the States with a big map
with blinking lights and
computers plotting out my route.

36:57.816 --> 37:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They would laugh if they saw how
seat-of-the-pants this is. This
is truly sort of strolling
across

37:03.288 --> 37:08.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the world, and seeing how far I
get before nightfall and then
looking for shelter. The

37:08.626 --> 37:12.163 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
world is, by and large,
a hospitable place.

37:12.163 --> 37:15.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Merab (ph), this is my friend
Hari from the United States.

37:15.967 --> 37:16.734 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

37:16.734 --> 37:18.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Hari.
Pleased to meet you.

37:18.803 --> 37:23.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Paul introduced me to his host
for the night before I arrived,
Merab Saaladze, a retired

37:23.541 --> 37:26.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
deputy governor of the
local municipality.

37:26.111 --> 37:30.148 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You just invited him into your
home. He's a total stranger.

37:30.148 --> 37:33.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MERAB SAALADZE, Georgia (through
translator): I asked him who he
was, and he said he was

37:33.918 --> 37:37.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from the U.S., so I
immediately invited them in.

37:37.122 --> 37:41.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is it common
to be this hospitable, to take
in a stranger?

37:41.826 --> 37:43.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MERAB SAALADZE: To me,
it was the first time.

37:43.962 --> 37:45.897 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

37:45.897 --> 37:51.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: After tea and
a bit more conversation, we set
out for the next waypoint,

37:51.503 --> 37:55.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the ancient village of Dmanisi
about six miles away, which we
will tell you more about in

37:55.039 --> 37:57.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
our next story.

37:57.375 --> 38:01.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: So, basically, there is no
shortcut. Merab said, well, yes,
you have to cross the

38:01.146 --> 38:01.779 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
river.

38:01.779 --> 38:02.247 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:02.247 --> 38:05.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SALOPEK: OK.

38:05.049 --> 38:10.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But, as we
soon found out, even the most
precise directions need
updating,

38:10.622 --> 38:17.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which we were given by a man
with hands stained from a
lifetime of gathering walnuts.

38:17.662 --> 38:21.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that, says Salopek,
is just part of the plan.

38:21.432 --> 38:25.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have got GPS, you have got
maps, you have got guides. You
are still going the wrong

38:25.036 --> 38:25.570 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
way sometimes.

38:25.570 --> 38:27.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SALOPEK: Yes.

38:27.872 --> 38:33.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Being found is overrated. Being
a little lost is good, because
it keeps you alert, keeps

38:33.411 --> 38:36.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you looking around. It keeps you
scanning the horizons about to
find your bearings,

38:36.981 --> 38:40.318 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and you are not sleepwalking
through the world.

38:40.318 --> 38:45.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how many
pairs of shoes do you think you
have gone through?

38:45.156 --> 38:49.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: This is the
fourth. Somebody brought me
these from the States, so
they're

38:49.194 --> 38:51.796 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
kind of special.

38:51.796 --> 38:56.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Do you get
tired by the end of an average
day, or has your body gotten

38:56.801 --> 38:58.203 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
used to this hiking pace?

38:58.203 --> 38:59.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SALOPEK: I do.

38:59.938 --> 39:05.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It depends on my physical
condition. You know, look, the
walk has kind of turned into my

39:05.343 --> 39:09.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
life, so it's a complicated
question to answer. It's like
you -- you have good weeks and
bad

39:09.280 --> 39:09.581 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
weeks.

39:09.581 --> 39:10.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

39:10.348 --> 39:11.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: I think I'm
in pretty good condition.

39:11.616 --> 39:13.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

39:13.785 --> 39:18.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: But I get tired,
and "my job" -- in quotes -- is
to write, not just really

39:18.823 --> 39:23.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to walk. So, at the end of the
day, it takes a special effort
to sit down and write a story.

39:23.695 --> 39:27.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My project, to walk across
the world for seven years.

39:27.899 --> 39:31.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Those stories,
dispatches from this ambling
Eden, are being followed

39:31.202 --> 39:35.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
online by a growing group
of digital companions.

39:35.807 --> 39:42.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Young people in particular,
students, catch up with Salopek
along the way. The tools of

39:42.046 --> 39:48.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the trade are the heaviest thing
he carries in his backpack: a
laptop, cameras, notebooks

39:48.186 --> 39:54.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and not more than a single
change of clothes. He stops
every 100 miles to record a
milestone,

39:54.158 --> 39:59.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a panoramic photo in this case
that includes an exhausted
"NewsHour" crew and a wayward

39:59.197 --> 40:04.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pig, then some video, and a
brief interview with the nearest
person.

40:04.335 --> 40:11.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This one, number 29, after 2,800
air miles traveled, came outside
a truck driver's house

40:11.643 --> 40:16.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
near a Georgian mining town. And
after a few questions and a
handshake, Salopek is again

40:16.681 --> 40:20.151 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on his way, the rhythm restored.

40:20.151 --> 40:23.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What makes a human want to
go over the next ridge?

40:23.721 --> 40:26.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Ah, the eternal
question, the one that probably
doesn't have a rational

40:26.557 --> 40:29.794 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
answer through science.

40:29.794 --> 40:35.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The walk is part of that
exploration, the impulse, not
even rational to know what's

40:35.867 --> 40:40.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over the mountain. Why -- why
paddle into the sea? We have set
out again and again,

40:40.672 --> 40:43.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and nobody came back, and yet we
still set out. And one
scientist, geneticist said,
we're

40:43.708 --> 40:47.211 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
just crazy.

40:47.211 --> 40:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that magical,
wonderful craziness is part of
the joy of this project. It's
something

40:51.649 --> 40:54.085 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that also binds us together.

40:54.085 --> 40:57.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour," I'm Hari Sreenivasan
in Southern Georgia.

40:57.889 --> 41:02.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Places
we never get to see.

